nesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. State regimes' attempts to co-opt the concept or reject it as alien to "Asian values" have apparently not turned out as expected. This is evident from the fact that many Southeast Asian citizens are inspired by the civil society concept and now engage in public discourse and participation. The experience of civil society in Southeast Asia shows that its impact -- or lack of impact -- on democratization and democracy depends on a variety of factors not only within civil society itself, but also within the state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCivil societyzSoutheast Asia. 0aPolitical culturezSoutheast Asia. 0aReligion and politicszSoutheast Asia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBanpasirichote, Chantana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarroll, John J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuan, Lee Hock, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeng, Russell Hiang-Khng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHock Guan, Lee, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKoh, Gillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLan, Thung Ju, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLing, Ooi Giok, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartinez, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRamasamy, P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSobritchea, Carolyn I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYan, Lai Suat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.